1. “Recursive patterns trapped in water”

That phrase actually describes something real in fluid physics.

Vortices and whirlpools are self-reinforcing feedback loops in a moving fluid.

Simplified:

flow → rotation → pressure change → stronger rotation

The pattern keeps recreating itself as long as energy flows through the system.

That’s why a whirlpool looks like a stable shape made of constantly changing water.
The water changes every moment, but the pattern persists.

In dynamical systems this is called an attractor.

⸻

2. “A vector trapped in a triangle”

That sounds like you’re picturing constraints shaping motion.

In physics and mathematics:
	•	A vector represents direction and magnitude.
	•	A triangle can represent a system of constraints or boundaries.

When vectors interact within constraints, you often get cycles or stable loops.

For example:

force A
+ force B
+ force C
= equilibrium

Triangular relationships show up everywhere—from structural engineering to navigation.

